spec: mp3226
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(multiprocessing)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/multiprocessing.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/multiprocessing.html"
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/multiprocessing.managers.html"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 662 (mp3226): __radd__, __rsub__, __rmul__ dict-presence (reflected arithmetic) for multiprocessing types."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Classes covered: multiprocessing.Process, pool.Pool, pool.AsyncResult, pool.MapResult, managers.SyncManager, managers.BaseListProxy, managers._BaseDictProxy, managers._BaseSetProxy."
    - "Key finding (__radd__): all 8 multiprocessing classes return false for __radd__. multiprocessing.Process manages a subprocess lifecycle (start/join/terminate/kill); reflected addition is undefined for process objects. pool.Pool dispatches work to worker processes; n + pool is not a defined operation. pool.AsyncResult and pool.MapResult are result handles; reflected addition is absent. managers.BaseListProxy proxies list — list does NOT define __radd__ (Python's list defines __add__ for concatenation, but not the reflected version; n + list is not a valid operation since int.__add__ does not handle list, and list has no __radd__ to fall back to). managers._BaseDictProxy proxies dict — dict defines neither __add__ nor __radd__. managers._BaseSetProxy proxies set — set does not define __radd__ (sets are not sequences and do not support + concatenation from either side). managers.SyncManager: server process hosting shared objects; no arithmetic protocol defined."
    - "Key finding (__rsub__): all 8 multiprocessing classes return false for __rsub__. Reflected subtraction is the mirror of __sub__. multiprocessing types define no __sub__ (confirmed false in wave 658), so __rsub__ is also absent. Process/Pool/AsyncResult/MapResult are process-management and result-handle types. managers.BaseListProxy proxies list — list defines no __sub__ or __rsub__. managers._BaseDictProxy proxies dict — dict defines no arithmetic operators. managers._BaseSetProxy proxies set — set defines __sub__ for set difference (s - t), but _BaseSetProxy does NOT have __rsub__ in its own __dict__; the proxy uses the _method IPC callthrough for all set operations."
    - "Key finding (__rmul__): all 8 multiprocessing classes return false for __rmul__. Reflected multiplication (__rmul__) is invoked when n * obj is attempted. multiprocessing types define no __mul__ (confirmed false in wave 658), so __rmul__ is equally absent. Critical note on managers.BaseListProxy: in wave 658 (mp3166), BaseListProxy.__mul__ was confirmed TRUE because list defines __mul__ for repetition (list * n), and BaseListProxy forwards this operator. However, list does NOT define __rmul__ — Python's list type has no __rmul__ in its __dict__. Therefore BaseListProxy also has no __rmul__ in its __dict__. n * BaseListProxy would require BaseListProxy.__rmul__, which does not exist."
    - "Proxy class note — BaseListProxy: wave 658 found BaseListProxy.__add__ = true and BaseListProxy.__mul__ = true (forwarding list's + and * operators). However, list does not define __radd__ or __rmul__; Python's list type supports left-side concatenation (list + list) and left-side repetition (list * n), but NOT reflected versions. n + list raises TypeError because int.__add__ does not handle list, and list has no __radd__. n * list uses int.__mul__ which handles int * list directly — no __rmul__ dispatch is needed. Since list has no __radd__/__rmul__ in its __dict__, BaseListProxy has none either."
    - "All 24 values in this wave are false. multiprocessing is a process-based concurrency library; its entire API is expressed through explicit method calls, subprocess lifecycle management, and IPC — never through Python's reflected arithmetic operators."
    - "Cross-wave summary for mp subjects:"
    - "  Wave 658 (mp3166): __add__/__sub__/__mul__ — BaseListProxy __add__=true, __mul__=true; others false."
    - "  Wave 659 (mp3181): __truediv__/__floordiv__/__mod__ — all false for all 8."
    - "  Wave 660 (mp3196): __pow__/__lshift__/__rshift__ — all false for all 8."
    - "  Wave 661 (mp3211): __and__/__or__/__xor__ — all false for all 8."
    - "  Wave 662 (mp3226): __radd__/__rsub__/__rmul__ — all false for all 8."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __radd__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__radd__')
#
# All 8 multiprocessing classes return false for __radd__.
# Process/Pool/AsyncResult/MapResult: process-management and result-handle
#   types; reflected addition is not defined for any of them.
# managers.BaseListProxy: proxies list — list does NOT define __radd__.
#   Python's list supports list + list (via __add__) and n * list (via int's
#   __mul__ directly), but n + list triggers int.__add__ which rejects list,
#   and list has no __radd__ fallback. Therefore BaseListProxy has no __radd__.
# managers._BaseDictProxy: proxies dict — dict defines no __add__ or __radd__.
# managers._BaseSetProxy: proxies set — set has no __radd__; sets do not
#   support + concatenation from either side.
# managers.SyncManager: server process; no arithmetic protocol defined.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

table mp3226.radd:
  description: "multiprocessing types __radd__ dict-presence checks; wave 662"
  kind: python_call_eq
  version: ">=3.9"
  error_model: python_exceptions
  category: dict_contains
  id_prefix: mp3226

  columns: [id, function, args, expected]
  rows:
    - ["mp3226001", operator.contains, [multiprocessing.Process.__dict__,                 "__radd__"], false]
    - ["mp3226002", operator.contains, [multiprocessing.pool.Pool.__dict__,               "__radd__"], false]
    - ["mp3226003", operator.contains, [multiprocessing.pool.AsyncResult.__dict__,        "__radd__"], false]
    - ["mp3226004", operator.contains, [multiprocessing.pool.MapResult.__dict__,          "__radd__"], false]
    - ["mp3226005", operator.contains, [multiprocessing.managers.SyncManager.__dict__,    "__radd__"], false]
    - ["mp3226006", operator.contains, [multiprocessing.managers.BaseListProxy.__dict__,  "__radd__"], false]
    - ["mp3226007", operator.contains, [multiprocessing.managers._BaseDictProxy.__dict__, "__radd__"], false]
    - ["mp3226008", operator.contains, [multiprocessing.managers._BaseSetProxy.__dict__,  "__radd__"], false]

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __rsub__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__rsub__')
#
# All 8 multiprocessing classes return false for __rsub__.
# Process/Pool/AsyncResult/MapResult/SyncManager: process-management types
#   with no arithmetic semantics of any kind.
# managers.BaseListProxy: proxies list — list defines no __sub__ or __rsub__.
# managers._BaseDictProxy: proxies dict — dict defines no arithmetic operators.
# managers._BaseSetProxy: proxies set — set defines __sub__ for set difference
#   (s - t), but _BaseSetProxy does NOT have __rsub__ in its own __dict__.
#   The reflected subtraction would require n - proxy, but set does not
#   define __rsub__ either; the proxy's _method IPC callthrough handles
#   set-difference as a named method, not as an operator dunder.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

